segments.text: I am Deborah Parks interviewing Mr. Herschel Burgess for the History of College Station Project at the Community Savings and Loan Branch Office on March 16, 1983, 3 PM, Side 1.
OK, where were you born?
I was born in Montague County, Texas.
February the 24th, 1907.
I'm sorry, 1905.
I guess you didn't have to volunteer that, but that's fine.
Were your parents from that same area?
Yes.
Yes, my father was a veteran in the Spanish-American War.
My mother was born there, I suppose.
My mother died when I was really young.
I never did know much about my mother's family.
But he was a veteran in the Spanish-American War.
Well, yes, he was a soldier in the Spanish-American War.
And what did he do for a living?
Farmer.
He was a farmer.
So therefore you worked on the farm when you were younger?
Yes, yes.
What type of things did you raise?
Everything that a farm in West Texas, agricultural products, feed stuff, cotton, cattle, of course we had cattle, ranch.
Okay.
How much formal education did you have since you worked on the farm?
Were you able to go to high school?
Yes, I went to school in Little Town of Mundy, Texas, Knox County.
In 1923, I came to Allen Academy here in Bryan, and that's where I got my more formal education, here in Bryan.
Allen Academy at that time was a military high school.
Oh, I see.
Why did you decide to go to Allen Academy?
Well, that's a long story.
It involved athletics.
I lived with the sweetest old aunt in the world in the little town of Mundy.
And she really loved me and took care of me.
I got interested in track and athletics.
I won the county meet for the little high school on Monday, and they sent me to the district meet in Vernon, Texas.
And I won there, and they made a lot of money to send me to Austin for the high school track meet.
I went on my own.
They made enough money to pay me away, but I didn't have a coach.
Oh, OK. All right.
The preliminaries of the track meet is on Friday in Austin.
Still are, I suppose.
That day I had a pretty good day in running in the dashes.
And then on Saturday, which is a final, a gentleman by the name of Charlie Hudson got a hold of me and took me over to his little gang.
And he was from Bryan, Texas.
He had been the athletic coach at Bryan.
And that summer, he had already contracted.
This was in May of 1923.
He had contracted to go to Allen Academy as an athletic coach.
And he made friends with me and took me over and gave me some instructions.
And I had a pretty good day.
And when I went about my business, I worked through the harvest fields that summer of 23.
And Mr. Hudson got in touch with me by mail.
He had my name and address and told me he had a job that would pay my expenses if I'd come to Allen Academy.
That would be the fall of 23.
And with that, I accepted that proposition and came to Allen Academy.
And so you were an athlete then?
Yes.
Did you attend more state championship?
I mean, did you win any type of?
Well, we...
We had a fine track team here at Allen Academy.
And that spring, Allen had a track team that was good enough that they qualified for track meet, for some meet events in Chicago for the National Scholastic Meet.
And they sent me up there.
Oh, really?
Chicago?
Yes, I won the second and 220-yard dash, I believe it was, and third, the 100-yard dash.
Well, that's wonderful.
And on the way from Chicago, that would be in the spring of 24, wouldn't it?
That would be the spring of 24.
And I worked in farming one thing or another during the summer of 24, then came back to Allen Academy that year.
We had a fine athletic team, football.
I had never played football until I came to Allen Academy.
And I was invited to come out for the team, and did, and made the team.
We had a good team in 24.
We, among other teams that we played, was a Texas A&M freshman.
Oh, you did?
You played the freshman?
I had a pretty good day against the freshman, Mr. Bible, who was head coach at Texas A&M at that time, Mr. D-X Bible.
shook hands with him and I met him and kept in contact with him.

And then when school, when I graduated Allen Academy in 1925, I worked again in the harvest fields as I generally did in summers and then came to Allen Academy, I mean to Texas A&M in the fall of 25 as a freshman.
Were you on some kind of football team?
Yes.
Oh, that's wonderful.
Well, scholarships such as we had those days, it doesn't like to wear that, but I had a little old job that helped me pay my expenses and pay the tuition and all.
So the freshmen didn't participate in varsity sports at that time.
We just played as freshmen.
Then, of course, in my sophomore year, which would be this fall of 26, then I was on the varsity team from then on until I graduated.
What was your degree?
What degree did you get?
A business degree.
Is that when you got interested in real estate then?
Or how did you get interested?
All right.
My athletics, I'm indebted very largely to athletics
scholarship for my education, whatever I got, because I went out for track and football.
We had some fine teams when I was here.
I was also taken into the Athletic Hall of Fame a few years ago.
Well, that's wonderful.
Well, it is for me.
That's a great honor, great achievement for me.
Now, you asked about real estate.
I graduated from A&M in 1929, which was a bad time.
Depression was coming on, and there wasn't very many of us that got jobs.
I was able to get a job with the United States Agriculture Department.
You've heard of the Mediterranean fruit fly?
Yes.
Well, that year it was tacking.
the Rio Grande Valley from Mexico, and the government was hiring, but I had some courses in, and I can speak Spanish, and so I was out of 15 or 20 boys in our class that got a job that year.
I got a job in Brownsville, and I stayed down there about a year or so, and as young men will do,
I got to courting.
I was going to ask you about that.
And of course courting will lead to marriage.
And I married in October of 1930.
Married that President Walton's daughter.
Oh, you did?
And her name is?
Ethel, E-T-H-Y-L. Ethel.
Walton.
And then I moved here.
And got into real estate activity on the south side of the NM campus.
Bought a tract of land down there, 75, 8 acres.
And cut it into lots and blocks.
Sold it as residential property.
That was before the city was organized.
And that was quite a problem, quite a job to do all of that.
I was going to ask you about how
How did you handle these type of things before?
Well, I'd had courses leading up to that helpful thing.
I had economics.
I wasn't called agricultural engineering then, but it was a business course.
And I took economics and some surveying and a course in banking and one thing or another.
And that all helped me.
I, of course, relied on friends more than anything else.
For some reason or other, the Lord has given me an abundance of friends.
Some of them had money, and they helped me out buying this property.
There wasn't any city here, and it made it very tough.
I had to put in on streets and all the utilities.
That's what I was wondering.
Yeah.
So...
Your Oakwood Realty Company?
Yes.
When you bought that 75 acres?
That's right.
I formed a corporation.
And what year was that?
That was 1933.
My 32, I guess, 1932, formed that corporation.
And subdivided that tract of land.
It was on the south side of the A&M campus.
Then undertook to...
Got some utilities in there.
And how do you do that?
Well, take water, for example.
Wasn't any kind of a public water system here.
And I was able to talk to the board directors of A&M.
Let me tie on to the A&M system for water.
And of course, I had to pay for all that, the pipe and get it under the ground.
install all the supplies for it.
So you built from the south side to the A&M campus border?
Well, I joined the A&M campus on the south side, but I had to lay the water lines from their water supply system, their wells, to the land, and then that's across the south side of the campus now.
Oh, where you see the kids playing ball out there?
Oh, yeah.
It's on campus now then?
Where you joined in, where they're out there playing ball?
Well, that's A&M property, my property.
You know Jersey Street?
Right.
Well, Jersey was a dirt road at that time.
And then my property was from Jersey on down that way.
So you had to personally lay the water lines and then A&M?
And pay for the pipe and the water and the labor and so forth.
Same for the sewer system.
We had to put in the sewer system.
Each residence, they're required to have a septic tank.
I think you probably know what a septic tank is.
A septic tank's a
a whole rectangular piece as big as this table here, but even deeper.
And the effluent from the sewer lines and the commodes and the drains in the house went into the septic tank.
And that was disposed of.
Then we had a line to it that carried the effluent out from the septic tank into a purifying plant.
We had, way down there, about half a mile away, had put that in as a purification system.
So the sewer didn't go to A&M.
No.
You put in another plant yourself.
We put in another stewarded disposal system altogether.
And then, of course, we got electricity from the university at the time.
And you had to put in the lines?
Had to put in the poles, the lines, and all of that.
Well, did they agree to do that if you had so many residents living, you know, getting so many residents?
Or did it help to, I guess you knew,
President Walton, your father-in-law, did that help?
Well, it probably did.
I didn't deal with him.
I dealt with the board.
They had to prove everything they did.
The gas, of course, we got the gas supply from the Lone Star Gas Company, which is still here, of course.
And we had to put in the pipe for that.
Very expensive undertaking at that time.
And still is, of course, more expensive than ever.
But it's very most difficult to not have any money to operate with.
I'd sell a lot and use that to do something else.
Oh, I see.
But the board of AM didn't say that we'll allow you to hook up to our utility, say you have 10 residents in your area?
No.
No, they didn't make any restrictions?
No, they didn't.
They had to just do it by the residents or by whatever.
Okay.
Just whatever.
Now I did try to develop the property in contiguous joints, contiguous parts, so that I have the utilities there and it's moving 75, 80 feet to another house and so on.
They were, the people before this time, the faculty, basically lived on campus, didn't they?
Yes, there's very few that lived off the campus, very few.
And that was my proposition, to give them an opportunity to have their own home off the campus.
They couldn't own a home on the campus.
The university owned all the residence property on the campus, on the A&M property.
They couldn't own it.
And what they rented it.
They had certain houses available for certain professors or employees.

dean's houses and all of that you know they had dean's row where the deans lived oh they they had a certain section for the dean or a certain house that's where the president's house is now you know see there's there's homes all through there then most of them are moving away you don't see any homes in there well were the board of directors interested in getting people to move off was it oh yes they helped them they'd be whatever assistance they could to get them to
provide their own homes.
They encouraged ownership of homes.
And that, well, in about 1933, President Roosevelt was elected.
The impression was awful enough.
And he created what they called the Federal Housing Administration.
And the purpose of that Federal Housing Administration was to help people own their homes.
And I took advantage of that system as best I could.

I had a friend who was a chief officer in the Houston District, and he helped me get lined up with the Federal Housing Administration and some of that Folkwood addition that I had developed down at the Oakwood Realty Company that we were talking about.
It was the first FHA-approved area between Houston and Dallas, and this man helped me
He helped me with that.
I can't say his first name.
H-U-M-P-H-R-I-E-S. About the 26th class, the 27th class of A&M.
No, they didn't have any money to lend.
I get that.
I had loan connections, mostly through the American General Insurance Company in Houston.
they would make a loan for a house for proper anyone if the FHA would guarantee the loan to be paid.
So for example, if you wanted to buy a house, and it was a very modern scheme up to date, up to that time, you could build a very fine house for $10,000, $20,000, the best in the area.
The lenders at that time were insurance companies and mortgage companies.
They'd loan about half that.
If you loaned $12,000, they'd lend about $6,000.
And the rules of repayment was 10 years.
You had to pay it back monthly in a 10-year period.
The FHA come along.
Instead of loaning 50%, they'd loan 90%.
So your $10,000 house, you'd need $1,000 to pay down.
Generally, if you had the lot, that was enough.
Then they made the payments up to 20 years, instead of 10 years.
And the interest rate was 5%, 5.5% instead of 8.5% or 9%.
And that revolutionized the home building.
And I took advantage of that.
And it made it easy for the profs, for the professors, and other A&M employees to buy their own homes.
And they just feel that's about a little dish of nut down there pretty quick.
Well, so really, you
gained a great advantage by being aware of the needs on campus and what the government was providing?
That's right.
And availability of money at the very best possible rates for the people.
And it worked fine.
And we just had things going all the time.
And then about 1938, I sold out that, developed it, and then bought a piece of land
here on the north side of the campus.
And we called that addition North Oakwood.
The other was just plain Oakwood.
But on the north end, we called it North Oakwood.
And I went in and developed that on the same idea.
It wasn't in the city either, either Bryan or College.
It's in the city of Bryan now.
Oh, it is?
Yeah.
To get you located maybe where it is, do you know where it is?
That was my first business.
That was my first little business development.
What do you call it?
A mall?
That was my first mall.
I started that in 1938.
And does it have, is it Brookside that runs through?
Yeah, that's my street.
I named that street.
Brookside and all those other streets in there.
Brookside Drive.
And so in 38, that didn't belong to Brian.
No, Brian's city limits didn't come out that far.
I had to do it, poor boy, if you will, just like I did the air on the south side.
I had to put in my own streets, dug my own water well, couldn't get it from A&M.
I had to dig my own water well and had an elevated tank, furnish water to the residents to begin with.
And that moved real fast.
real fast farmland under the same FHA operation as they're doing on the south side.
People that you might know live, lots and lots of A&M people.
Live in that area?
Live there now and did then.
They were primarily the ones that bought the property and built lovely homes.
It's very close to the university.
Yeah, that's right.
What did College Station, I guess,
Right before it was incorporated, what did it look like?
Was it basically open prairie?
Well, except on the campuses, just simply rural country, just open farmland.
On the east gate here, you know, that was all farmland.
It was in cotton, and there wasn't any residences.
Texas Avenue was a dirt road.
Jersey Street was a dirt and gravel road, which wasn't near as wide as it is now, just a country lane, that's all it was.
And at the north gate where the post office is over there, you know, that post office was placed there about, oh what, 1935 or 36.
You know where the post office is.
And there's two or three stores across the street from it.
The grocery store,
Been there a good many years, called Luke and Charlie.
And there was a drug store there.
Lipscomb?
Well, not at first.
Lipscomb wasn't there.
Casey and Sparks had a little pharmacy there, really.
A fellow named Burtis, B-U-R-T-I-S, not money, ran the store.
And then Lipscomb did come there, and they built his father-in-law, who was Dr. E.J.
Kyle.
I'm sorry.
Dr. E.J.
wasn't Dr. Lipscomb's father-in-law.
They were related.
They were related?
No, they're not related at all.
But that Dean Kyle was the agriculture dean at A&M, and he built this two-story building there.
And Lipscomb did operate a drugstore out of that two-story building.
Mrs. Lipscomb still lives on the south side in my addition that I've developed down there in Oakwood Addition.
I sold them a home down there.
It was about 35, 36, somewhere back in there.
Well, a lot of residents, it seems like a lot of residents still live there.
Oh, yes.
It's full of some of the old-timers.
That's good.
They were happy with it.
Yeah.
We used to have a cage there.
Lee Street was a, I built the first house on Lee Street, and we didn't even have Lee Street in there.
We had it designated, but it hadn't been graded out.
How did you provide for the streets?
You had to build those too?
Yes, I had to put them in.
Contract with some company to lay?
Yes, I had to contract with a street building company.
They were very poor.
What were they made of?
They had to grade it up, just had the street graded up.
And then made them all surface by gravel.
They weren't paved, I don't suppose, until probably after World War II.
I'm not quite sure about that.
And the city did that then?
Yes.
It was incorporated then.
Yes, the city was organized about 1938, wasn't it?
38, right.
And then the city then bought the utility lines
from me and we took over the streets and maintained them and paid them.
But originally you as the developer had to provide for that.
That's right.
We had a little taxing system that we charged so much per lot
really is on a front-foot basis.
If you had a 50-foot lot, you'd pay taxes on the basis of 50 foot.
If I had a 100-foot lot, then I'd pay on the 100 feet and so forth.
How were they kept up?
Just had a private man live down around Wellborn.
That included the sewage pickup or garbage pickup.
There's always a little comical comedy attached to that.
This old black man had a wagon and mules, and it was his job to pick up the garbage.
We paid him out of this tax money.
I handled that, but I collected the taxes.
They had a taxing system, and I paid for the garbage pickup and upkeep of the streets.
They'd have to be graded every so often.
And I paid for that out of this tax money.
This old Negro, his name was Rum, R-U-M.
He had this team and a mule and a wagon.
It had about three or four kids.
And they were kids, but I say the oldest, one was, say, 11, 12, then on down.
And they'd always start in the wagon.
Another little white kid would follow them around in that wagon.
And he had two or three dogs that he lashed onto the wagon with a string or something that they just
It's kind of a comedy to see him coming.
To see him going down the street to pick up the trash?
Yeah, the kids following, hollering, carrying on.
And he did that for several years.
Well, so the city is organizing.
The city took over.
Oh, that's wonderful.
That's the type of thing.
Well, it's real country.
It's real backward country doing it.
But we had about all we could do in those days.
But that's the type of thing that people like me do not, you know.
Don't realize it now.
Just don't realize.
In fact, it was a pretty hard time.
There was no fire level.
We had a fire on Lee Street.
An architectural prop lived in the house.
I believe his name was Jack Finney.
His house caught fire.
There's a dry lake, which you happen to know on the south side of the company.
It's called Bryson Pond or Bryson Park now.
Was it full of water then?
Yes, it was full of water.
Oh, okay.
Yeah, I know where that is.
And two or three fires we had, the water was pumped from that pond, from that lake, and the hose was stretched out to wherever the fire was.
And it wasn't much of a fire system, but that's all they had.
Oh, you couldn't depend on the university?
No, not at that time.
Not at that time.
So the only thing you had was just the pond?
That's the pond.
That's the fire water we had.
We didn't have any lines big enough to carry the water.
Six-inch lines.
The fire plug didn't have any fire plug to attach it to.
So it was pretty rugged living.
But so the Oakwood started about like 1932, you would say?
No.
Let's say, I think we got the corporation in 1933.
Let's say 1934.
Oakwood really started developing that area in there.
And this is the way they had to live until you incorporated the city.
That's right.
My house is known as 112 Lee Avenue, and it was the first house on Lee Street.
That's 1935 when we built it.
But it wasn't the first house on the south side, was it?
Oh, no, no.
Because you have College Park.
No, the College Park now.
College Park was developed, started about 1923 or 24.
Of course, I had nothing to do with that.
That was some college professors owned, organized what they called College Park Development Company.
Dr. Clark?
Yes.
Who?
Dr. Clark.
Dr. F.B.
Clark.
He was one of the organizers.
And Dr. Burchard was a chemistry trial.
He was in it.
And about three or four others whose names are kind of left now.
I can't see the names anymore.
But there's five of them, as I remember.
And they developed what is known as College Park Edition.
About 1923.
It started about 1923 or 1924.
Well, later on, College Park and Oakwood have a joint association.
What year was that?
Yes.
I bought the unsold lots in College Park, Oakwood Realty Company did, in 1936, let's say.
They had, oh, maybe 100, 150 unsold lots, undeveloped lots, and I bought them.
and then proceeded to develop them and sell them out as Oakwood Realty Company.
We connected streets.
It would be interesting, very interesting, if we had an abstract of College Park.
The map's entirely different now from what it was then.
They had properties laid out for colored people, blacks.
Oh, really?
Yeah.
You know where Fairview Street is?
Do you?
Fairview Street ran off from the campus southward and came to a square like that.
Here's a street here.
And let's see.
This is Fairview.
This is what's now is Jersey Street.
Fairview Street ran down here and ran into a little
square like that.
This was designated as a Negro church.
Was it a church actually there?
Yeah, it was actually there.
To go around that you'd have to come down the street and go down like that.
This is the church and when I bought the lots I undertook to get rid of that sort of situation because fire trucks couldn't get down through there.
They hadn't even thought of that.
And we changed that around, and there was Negro people living along here.
And that was designated for them when they laid out College Park?
That's right.
Very interesting.
It is interesting.
Did you have that type of sectioning in Oakwood?
No.
No.
No, we didn't have that in Oakwood.
We didn't even...
There's been many additions here in the South, all through the South, and certainly in Texas.
In Brazos County, niggers were prohibited from buying property, and that's been outlawed now.
Right.
Yeah.
And FHA, Federal Housing Administration, had a lot to do with it.
If you...
What do you call it?
What word am I trying to say?
Discriminate?
That word?
Discriminate?
Discriminate.
That's the word.
If you discriminate against anybody for race or color or religion, it was a violation of law.
You couldn't get any money to build a house through FHA.
So I never did get in there.
But anyway, when I bought that, I took all this out.
Got these people that lived here.
And...
traded with them, traded property that, do you know where the Lincoln School is down on the south side?
That's where they went.
That was the Negro property.
And most of them came from this little area right there.
So when you bought it, they moved from this area to Lincoln?
When you bought the rest of College Park, the Negro families living here moved to Lincoln?
Yes, I gave them property down there for property here.
And then, like, you went ahead and just... We just took this out.
We just took that and straightened it on out and made it a through street and made these residential lots.
Oh, that's very interesting.
Yes, it'd be interesting for you to develop, and you must do it if you...
I don't know what extent for your writing the school thing might not require it, but in a book it'd be interesting.
Because certain people couldn't associate with Negroes.
When you bought a lot from Dr. Clark and those patients over there, if a white and a dark and a black person associated, they got married.
They automatically gave title.
They lost the title to their property.
I don't know that that ever came.
I don't think it stood up in any kind of law.
But that was what was in those abstracts when I bought the clock.
Of course, I immediately took it out.
And they weren't even permitted to associate together as dates, for example.
And certain intermarriages were absolutely prohibited.
I can imagine.
I mean, you have a certain sense of that today, but what is that, 50 years ago would be even more.
Yeah, 60, 70 years ago, maybe.
And you know a lot of those people from the North, too, that made those sort of rules.
I know.
Even though they were fighting for... For freedom of the slave people.
I had a question.
I ran across some information.
They said, I guess, area further south was owned by the Federal Land Bank of Houston.
Does that ring a bell?
I had no knowledge of the Federal...
Well, I'm sure the Federal Land Bank owned property throughout the county.
The Federal Land Bank didn't really own land to develop or to farm.
It made loans if you had a farm and you needed some equipment.
Or maybe the whole farm.
You might borrow money from the federal land bank to buy the farm, or to buy farm machinery or equipment.
And of course, sometimes they had defaults where people failed to pay and they had to seize the land.
But they'd seize it and then repossess it, we say.
That's a term we use, repossess.
And then resend it to somebody else.
But I never knew of any federal...
land bank federal farm blown down in that area.
Well, it was in a newspaper and it made reference to the federal land bank and then the Whitesell estate.
Does that ring a bell?
What?
The Whitesell, W-E-I-N-Z-E-T-L estate.
No, I don't know anything about that.
Okay, that's fine.
You made me to make remarks.
Well, I was just wondering what were some of the factors that brought about the incorporation of .

Well, the principal factor was for the citizens to obtain the services that you can get from city organizations, such as police, for example, had no pleas, and the utilities, and maintenance of the utility streets.
other assets of the city office.
And it was necessary to have some sort of an organization to control.
We're just doing everything, you know.
Developers such as yourself.
Yeah, well, developers, yeah, such as me and others.
And they had no laws.
Might only build a barn right out in the middle of somebody's yard, you know.
They had no control.
There's plenty of urgent need for a city organization.
And I urged that the best I could as a youngster.
I never took any action in any of the city offices or city elections when I developed what we call West Park Edition over on next to the railroad over there.
You know, on the south side of the A&M campus, another little mall down there that I put in.
The south side?
South side.
South side shopping center there.
That's mine.
We didn't call them malls in those days.
We just called them shopping centers.
And the city was, I bought that property.
What day did I buy that property?
Oh, I must have been 38.
And the city was getting organized.
And they were going to have a zoning ordinance, zoning regulation.
That was a little unusual in this area of Texas.
I'm sure in the bigger cities, zoning was common.
Well, I had bought that tract of land there where this shopping center is, Southside Shopping Center.
Oh, there's 60, 70 acres back in there.
And it belonged to a Czech family.
Came from the old country.
They're very, very poor people.
Mrs. Hardricka?
No, that's another part.
I know the Hardrickas.
It wasn't Schwartz.
Schwartz is a family I bought the Oakwood property from.
I can't say it.
But anyway, this widow lived there about where, let me see.
there on the corner where that two-story building, I put that building there.
He had a little check in the house there.
There wasn't anything across the street on that A&M property, just blank.
She had one cow and some chickens.
Went around barefooted all the time.
Very poor.
And I bought that property from them.
And I paid what I thought was a big price for the property then, about $150 an acre.
But I thought the best chance of coming out on it was to Long Jersey Street there to make a little business center out of that.
And I drew up a plan of the area, lots of blocks and so forth.
And then across the front, Long Jersey Street there, designated as a commercial area.
The City of College Station was getting underway.
